Legs: Forefemur bearing posterodorsal, slightly irregular row of about 6 setae, these becoming progressively longer distally. Foretibia with 2 slightly stronger preapical setulae. Basitarsomere of foreleg with anteroventral row of setulae and a few stronger setulae ventrobasally. Midfemur in males with femoral organ anterodorsally and shortly proximal to middle (figs. 2 and 3 ). Femoral organ consisting of field of irregularly­placed tiny setulae of probably sensory function (
Brake 2000
). Midtibia with several stronger setulae and 1 seta preapically. Hindfemur enlarged, about 1.5–1.8 x as broad as fore­ and midfemur. Hindtibia as foretibia, with ventroapical comb of setulae. Basitarsomere of hindleg with several ventral rows of 3–5 setulae, with setulae flattened apically (fig. 4 ), and with few stronger setulae ventrobasally.
